The paper discusses community detection in dynamic networks, which is a topic that can be approached from various subfields of computer science. However, the focus on temporal interactions and the proposal of a formalism to capture intrinsically dynamic communities suggest that the paper is more likely to be classified under social and information networks (cs.SI) or systems and control (cs.SY). The use of empirical and synthetic datasets and the introduction of dynamic metrics also point towards data science (cs.DS) and machine learning (cs.LG) as possible sub-categories. Finally, the mention of community detection algorithms and sampling techniques suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the sub-field of algorithms and data structures (cs.DS).
